{"source_key":"sha256-166a6f077fd8acca604befa465c21cd9","record_index":133,"record_hash":"sha256:e5c98fde5fc1af5b738c48d81554bc32699154d0617bb5d99c81be1523ac7845","timestamp":"2026-05-21T19:54:30.666Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/agent-trail.md\n+# Agent Trail\n+\n+Agent Trail is the review-adjacent product surface for captured agent sessions.\n+It is the page a reviewer opens from a pull request to understand the agent work\n+behind a change.\n+\n+## Working Name\n+\n+Use **Agent Trail** for now.\n+\n+Good PR link text:\n+\n+- View Agent Trail\n+- Explore Agent Trail\n+- Agent Trail for this PR\n+\n+Avoid names like \"transcript\", \"audit log\", or \"provenance report\" for the\n+product surface. The page may contain transcript records and provenance facts,\n+but the user-facing promise is simpler: follow the useful trail behind this\n+change.\n+\n+## Product Shape\n+\n+A developer opens a pull request from GitButler or GitHub. GitButler adds a link\n+to the pull request. A reviewer clicks that link and lands on a GitButler-owned\n+web page for the Agent Trail.\n+\n+The page lets the reviewer explore captured agent context related to the pull\n+request:\n+\n+- prompts and requests from the human\n+- assistant responses and claims\n+- tool calls and tool results\n+- tests and validation attempts\n+- decisions and tradeoffs\n+- follow-up questions\n+- edge cases discussed or missed\n+\n+This is not primarily a chat transcript viewer. The transcript is the source of\n+truth, but the review experience should be organized around helping a reviewer\n+understand the change.\n+\n+## Core Question\n+\n+Agent Trail should answer:\n+\n+> What agent context helps me review this pull request?\n+\n+It should not claim:\n+\n+> This agent session authored this pull request.\n+\n+The language should stay evidence-based. Say that a session or turn is related\n+to a pull request, branch, review, or change. Do not present related agent data\n+as proof of authorship.\n+\n+## Entry Point\n+\n+The first expected entry point is a pull request link.\n+\n+Possible GitHub placement:\n+\n+- PR description link added by GitButler\n+- PR comment posted by GitButler\n+- check-run details link\n+- GitHub app panel, if that becomes available later\n+\n+The simplest first version is probably a PR description or bot comment link.\n+Check-run UI may be nicer later, but it adds product and permission complexity.\n+\n+## Data Source\n+\n+Agent Trail should build on `but-agentlog` primitives:\n+\n+- durable project-scoped agent sessions\n+- capture turns inside sessions\n+- transcript records inside turns\n+- observed branch, review, and change targets\n+- verified related-session lookup\n+- bounded turn and record hydration\n+\n+`but-agentlog` should remain the evidence layer. Agent Trail should live above\n+it as a product-specific projection and browsing layer.\n+\n+## Relationship Model\n+\n+One pull request may relate to many sessions. One session may relate to many\n+pull requests or branches.\n+\n+The durable object remains the project-scoped session. Pull requests, reviews,\n+branches, and changes should reference session or turn keys; they should not own\n+copies of transcript records.\n+\n+The first Agent Trail implementation can start from:\n+\n+1. pull request / review identifier\n+2. related branch or change identifiers\n+3. `but-agentlog` related-session lookup\n+4. verified related turns from stored observed targets\n+5. bounded transcript hydration for selected turns\n+\n+## Review Experience\n+\n+The default view should be compact and review-focused.\n+\n+Show:\n+\n+- what the human asked the agent to do\n+- what the agent said it changed\n+- what commands or tools it ran\n+- what validation passed or failed\n+- important decisions and tradeoffs\n+- warnings where the trail is weak or incomplete\n+\n+Do not default to dumping every message or every tool result. Exact records\n+should be available through drill-down.\n+\n+Useful sections:\n+\n+- Overview\n+- Timeline\n+- Prompts\n+- Claims\n+- Validation\n+- Open Questions\n+- Raw Records\n+\n+`Raw Records` should be secondary. It exists for evidence and debugging, not as\n+the main review page.\n+\n+## Ranking And Highlighting\n+\n+The page should rank or highlight likely relevant turns. Relevance is a product\n+decision above `but-agentlog`.\n+\n+Good signals:\n+\n+- direct review target observation\n+- direct change target observation\n+- direct branch target observation\n+- capture time near commits or PR updates\n+- prompts mentioning the feature, bug, branch, or files\n+- assistant claims about implementation or tests\n+- tool calls that run tests, builds, formatters, or linters\n+- later path or commit evidence, if added\n+\n+Weak signals:\n+\n+- backfilled turns with only capture-time environment snapshots\n+- broad sessions that span unrelated work\n+- sidecar review sessions that discuss the branch but did not implement it\n+- turns related only through current branch state\n+\n+The UI should expose why a turn is highlighted. Reviewers should not have to\n+guess why a session appears.\n+\n+## Privacy And Publication\n+\n+Agent Trail is more sensitive than local handoff because it is meant to be\n+opened by colleagues.\n+\n+Before publishing or linking:\n+\n+- records must be redacted\n+- local filesystem paths should not be exposed\n+- raw provider session ids should not be exposed\n+- hidden/system/developer prompts should not be exposed\n+- source records should stay bounded and redacted\n+- the user should understand that the trail may contain prompts and tool output\n+\n+The first product design needs an explicit publication boundary. Capturing data\n+into GitMeta does not automatically mean every pull request should expose a\n+public or team-visible Agent Trail.\n+\n+## Permissions\n+\n+Open question: who can view an Agent Trail?\n+\n+Possible policy:\n+\n+- same users who can view the repository\n+- same users who can view the pull request\n+- GitButler team/workspace members\n+- explicit share link recipients\n+\n+The first version should pick one simple rule and make it obvious. For private\n+repositories, defaulting to repository/PR visibility is probably the least\n+surprising.\n+\n+## Non-Goals\n+\n+- no claim that agent sessions authored the pull request\n+- no full transcript dump as the main experience\n+- no copying transcript records onto pull request targets\n+- no product-specific review payloads inside `but-agentlog`\n+- no magic generated summary as the source of truth\n+- no automatic public publishing just because capture succeeded\n+- no cryptographic audit or compliance story for v1\n+\n+## Open Questions\n+\n+- Should the PR link be posted by GitButler Desktop, a GitButler service, or a\n+  GitHub app?\n+- Does Agent Trail live at a stable URL per PR, per branch, or per generated\n+  snapshot?\n+- Should a trail update automatically as more agent sessions are captured?\n+- Should users be able to hide or exclude specific sessions before publishing?\n+- What is the minimum useful privacy review before sharing a trail?\n+- Should reviewers be able to ask follow-up questions against the trail?\n+- Should the page include generated summaries, or only deterministic previews\n+  and exact drill-down?\n+\n+## Implementation Boundary\n+\n+Keep the primitive crate boring.\n+\n+`but-agentlog` owns:\n+\n+- capture\n+- redaction\n+- GitMeta storage\n+- related-session lookup\n+- compact skim/read primitives\n+- bounded exact record reads\n+\n+Agent Trail owns:\n+\n+- PR/review entry point\n+- URL and publishing flow\n+- permission model\n+- review-specific ranking\n+- page layout and copy\n+- share-specific projection\n+- optional generated summaries\n+\n+If Agent Trail needs code in this repository, prefer a separate module or crate\n+layered above `but-agentlog`.\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md\n@@\n - handoff, where a session captured on one machine can later be read from GitMeta\n   and resumed on another machine or by another agent\n - review sharing, where a branch or pull request can later reference one or more\n-  project sessions for a GitButler web timeline\n+  project sessions for an [Agent Trail](agent-trail.md) review page\n@@\n - [Future Use Cases](future-use-cases.md)\n+- [Agent Trail](agent-trail.md) - review-adjacent PR link and browsing surface\n - [Including Turns In Agentlog](Including-turns.md) - current turn/index-based association direction\n - [Agent Session Handoff Design](handoff-design.md) - current `skim`/`show` handoff design\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md\n@@\n - [Agentlog Sync Lifecycle](agentlog-sync-lifecycle.md)\n - [Agent Session Handoff Design](handoff-design.md) - current `skim`/`show` handoff design\n+- [Agent Trail](agent-trail.md) - review-adjacent PR link and browsing surface\n - [Agentlog Maintainability Playbook](maintainability-playbook.md)\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-21T19:54:30.666Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}